Surgery is an essential part of the management of patients presenting with ovarian cancer. Diagnosis, staging, and therapy can be carried out at the time of laparotomy. Unfortunately, the disease often presents at an advanced stage and the outlook for patients is poor with an overall 5-year survival rate of 23%. This review focuses on the surgical management of advanced ovarian cancer and focuses on both primary, secondary, and intervention debulking surgery.
